<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="84" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="84">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="84">
This is the only known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baillon" authorityYear="1890" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Monanthotaxis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Monanthotaxis" order="Magnoliales" pageId="13" pageNumber="84" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">Monanthotaxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the Comoros and Mayotte. It is easily distinguished from almost all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baillon" authorityYear="1890" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Monanthotaxis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Monanthotaxis" order="Magnoliales" pageId="13" pageNumber="84" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">Monanthotaxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by having 6 staminodes alternating with 6 stamens, all in a single whorl. The only other species sharing that feature, viz. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baillon" authorityYear="1890" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Monanthotaxis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Monanthotaxis congoensis" order="Magnoliales" pageId="13" pageNumber="84" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="congoensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">Monanthotaxis congoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Baillon and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="P.H.Hoekstra" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Monanthotaxis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Monanthotaxis paniculata" order="Magnoliales" pageId="13" pageNumber="84" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paniculata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">Monanthotaxis paniculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
P.H.Hoekstra are very different. These have a single whorl of petals (vs two whorls in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="P. H. Hoekstra" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Monanthotaxis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Monanthotaxis komorensis" order="Magnoliales" pageId="13" pageNumber="84" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="komorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">Monanthotaxis komorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), inflorescences of raceme-like or panicle-like rhipidia, their young branches are densely covered with yellowish brown short hairs and they occur in Central Africa. The flowers of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verdcourt" authorityYear="1971" baseAuthorityName="Baill." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Monanthotaxis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Monanthotaxis glaucocarpa" order="Magnoliales" pageId="13" pageNumber="84" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glaucocarpa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">Monanthotaxis glaucocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Baill.) Verdc., a species from Madagascar, are not known. This species differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="P. H. Hoekstra" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Monanthotaxis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Monanthotaxis komorensis" order="Magnoliales" pageId="13" pageNumber="84" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="komorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="84">Monanthotaxis komorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having longer pedicels (&gt;30 mm vs 9 mm), longer stipes (7-9 mm vs 2.0-2.5 mm) and longer and bigger seeds (12-15 mm vs 6 mm). Further, the leaves are less elongate and the young branches are glabrous.
</paragraph>
